es =E2=80=9Chey, our boss is bad, I would be a good boss, I rented an offic=
e across the street,=C2=A0come with me and we=E2=80=99ll do a better job,=
=E2=80=9D and they come with you, did you do a hostile takeover=3F In some =
formal sense no: The old corporate entity still exists, and you don=E2=80=
=99t own it; the old firm=E2=80=99s contracts are still in force. But reall=
y the company=C2=A0<em>was=C2=A0</em>its employees, and their knowledge and=
=C2=A0client relationships, and if they all go with you then you got=C2=A0<=
em>most=C2=A0</em>of the company. The bankers will call their old clients a=
nd say =E2=80=9Chello we moved across the street and are a different legal =
entity, but really we=E2=80=99re still the same company with the same great=
 service, call me here instead,=E2=80=9D and the clients will mostly do tha=
t.=C2=A0</p> <p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This doesn=E2=80=99t happen too m=
uch. Lots of companies have, like, factories and equipment and stores, and =
you can=E2=80=99t just ask them to move across the street. Other companies =
are huge, and you couldn=E2=80=99t convince all the employees to move acros=
s the street; the corporate structure and its bureaucracy are necessary for=
 controlling that many people. Actual investment banks are mostly large lev=
ered financial institutions with big balance sheets, and you can=E2=80=99t =
move the balance sheet across the street.</p> <p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=
But there=C2=A0<em>are=C2=A0</em>some small companies whose assets really d=
o consist mostly of=C2=A0their employees=E2=80=99 knowledge and skills and =
relationships, and at those companies, if one charismatic leader doesn=E2=
=80=99t like corporate management and can convince most of the employees to=
 go with her, then she kind of can do a hostile takeover without corporate =
formalities. Something like this happens every now and then with law firms.=
</p> <p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I suppose the weirder case is where a sma=
ll company (1) consists mostly of its employees=E2=80=99 knowledge and skil=
ls and relationships and (2) has raised a ton of outside capital. Like, you=
 get 20 people together and you go out to investors saying =E2=80=9Cwe are =
so smart and have such good relationships, we=E2=80=99re gonna make a ton o=
f money, and we=E2=80=99re willing to give you a cut of it if you give us m=
oney now.=E2=80=9D The investors say =E2=80=9Cwow you <em>are</em> very sma=
rt, here=E2=80=99s a billion dollars=C2=A0for a 20% cut of what you=E2=80=
=99re up to.=E2=80=9D</p> <p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But you could all st=
ill walk away=3F In some sense you=E2=80=99d be leaving money on the table:=
 If investors gave you $1 billion for 20%, that means that the other 80% of=
 the firm =E2=80=94=C2=A0the part that you and your friends still own =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0is worth $4 billion, so you are abandoning your $4 billion equi=
ty stake if you go across the street and start over. On the other hand, if =
=E2=80=9Cthe firm=E2=80=9D was really just you and your friends and your pr=
ospects, then if you go across the street and start over, the=C2=A0<em>new=
=C2=A0</em>firm will be worth $5 billion (and the husk of the old firm will=
 be worth $0), and you=E2=80=99ll own all of it, so you=E2=80=99ll actually=
 come out ahead. Keep doing that trade over and over again.<a class=3D"foot=
note-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !importan=
t; display: inline-block;"> <span>[1]</span> </a> Presumably investors woul=
d eventually ask you for a non-compete.</p> <p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">An=
d then the even weirder case is an outside=C2=A0<em>acquirer</em>. A big co=
mpany comes to your small company and says =E2=80=9Cwe think your company i=
s worth $8 billion and we would like to own it=E2=80=9D and you say =E2=80=
=9Cgreat sure we would like $8 billion.=E2=80=9D And the big company says =
=E2=80=9Cokay so we=E2=80=99ll write a check for $1.6 billion to your outsi=
de investors, who own 20% of the company, and $6.4 billion to you, who own =
the other 80%.=E2=80=9D And you say =E2=80=9Cwell, wait, no. That $8 billio=
n valuation is just for=C2=A0<em>us</em>, for our knowledge and skills and =
relationships. That=E2=80=99s what you want: us. We are what you ascribe al=
l that value to. The outside investors aren=E2=80=99t bringing anything to =
the table; all they did was give us money a while ago. Tell you what, we=E2=
=80=99ll just abandon our old company and come to your company, and you can=
 pay us $7.5 billion of signing bonuses. You=E2=80=99ll get the thing you w=
ant =E2=80=94=C2=A0us =E2=80=94=C2=A0at a discount to fair value, and we=E2=
=80=99ll get paid more than we would for our equity in the old firm.=E2=80=
=9D</p> <p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is all a bit silly and nothing=C2=
=A0<em>really=C2=A0</em>works like that, though some tech industry =E2=80=
=9C<a href=3D"https://links.message.bloomberg.com/u/click=3F_t=3Df574328d4d=
0c4c359b90d8e49b10e21d&_m=3D995e2c8db6f743b7b4984aa376475103&_e=3D2KrFj1RYP=
