solid; background-color: #ccc;">acquihires</a>=E2=80=9D=C2=A0can get pretty=
 close.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #00=
0000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bo=
ttom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color=
: transparent !important; display: inline-block;"> <span>[2]</span> </a>In =
part this is because you can=E2=80=99t find too many cases of <em>pure=C2=
=A0</em>firms like this, firms that get 100% of their value from human capi=
tal and nothing else; in part because=C2=A0firms like this tend not to rais=
e lots of outside capital; and in part because, when they do, the outside i=
nvestors will generally get some safeguards (noncompete agreements, fiducia=
ry duties from the top employees, etc.) to prevent the human capital from v=
anishing.=C2=A0</p> <p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Still it=E2=80=99s a fun t=
hought experiment. Here is a dumb little footnote to the thought experiment=
: When the big company =E2=80=9Cacquires=E2=80=9D you and your friends by p=
aying you signing bonuses, is that an acquisition that triggers pre-merger =
